licuitne] ‘did your insolent language suffer me to cherish this benefit of yours as 1 did cherish it, and that too though you saw that you would hear such words as these from me?' the meaning is that Antony by his insolence had done his best to efface from Cicero's mind the recollection of the service that he had done him. ‘praesertim cum refers to per tuas contumeliam affronts which were the more wauton, as you knew that I could retaliate'. 19 tot dierum viam] this probably means that she travelled from Rome to Brundisium to meet Antony; this would take from 13 to 15 days, the distance being about 370 miles. See Prof. Palmer’s remarks on Horace's well-known journey, Sat. 1. 5. 103.

qui non] Cicero might have written quin here and before viderit, and also quin scierit, but wishing to negative the verb strongly, he prefers qui non: the difference may be seen in English ‘who was there but (quin) saw her? ², ‘who was there who did not (qui non) see her?'
